2014\u201318\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Scorpion (TV series)|Scorpion]]''\n|66 episodes\n|-\n|2018\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Yellowstone (U.S. TV series)|Yellowstone]]''\n|19 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Swamp Thing (2019 TV series)|Swamp Thing]]''\n|10 episodes, show cancelled after 1 episode\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television sports===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year \n!Title\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[2018 Australian Grand Prix|March 2018]]  \u2013 Present\n|Formula One\n|Official theme tune for [[Formula One]]\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Lego Universe]]''\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3]]''\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Need for Speed: The Run]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Far Cry 3]]''\n|Nominated- [[British Academy Games Awards|BAFTA Games Award for Best Audio Achievement]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Army of Two: The Devil's Cartel]]''\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Assassin's Creed IV: Black Flag]]''\n| Nominated- [[British Academy Games Awards|BAFTA Games Award for Best Original Music]]\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[F1 2018 (video game)|F1 2018]]''\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[F1 2019 (video game)|F1 2019]]''\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{BLP sources section|date=March 2017}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n!{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Composition for a Miniseries, Movie, or a Special]]\n| ''[[Last Call (2002 film)|Last Call]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards#Fangoria Chainsaw Awards|Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Score]]\n| ''[[Frailty (2001 film)|Frailty]]''\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Horror/Thriller Film]]\n| ''[[The Final Cut (2004 film)|The Final Cut]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n|[[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Film Composer of the Year]]\n|{{NA}}\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusiccritics.org/2010/03/ifmca-announces-winners-of-2009-awards/ |title=IFMCA: the International Film Music Critics Association \u2013 IFMCA announces winners of 2009 Awards |publisher=Filmmusiccritics.org |accessdate=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Horror/Thriller Film]]\n| ''[[The Killing Room]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Video Game or Interactive Media]]\n| ''[[Lego Universe]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| [[38th Daytime Emmy Awards#Outstanding Music Direction and Composition|Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Music Direction and Composition]]\n| ''[[Transformers: Prime]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Video Game or Interactive Media]]\n|''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013\n|[[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Film Composer of the Year]]\n|{{NA}}\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusiccritics.org/2014/02/ifmca-winners-2013/|title=IFMCA: the International Film Music Critics Association \u2013 IFMCA Winners 2013|publisher=Filmmusiccritics.org |accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for a Video Game or Interactive Media]]\n| ''[[Assassin's Creed IV: Black Flag]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[International Film Music Critics Association|International Film Music Critics Award for Best Original Score for an Action/Adventure/Thriller Film]]\n| ''Iron Man 3''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2014\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Music]]\n| ''Iron Man 3''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>[https://variety.com/2014/film/news/gravity-the-hobbit-the-desolation-of-smaug-lead-saturn-awards-noms-1201120744/ \"''Gravity'', ''The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug'' Lead Saturn Awards Noms\"]</ref>\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Music]]\n| ''[[Now You See Me (film)|Now You See Me]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]]\n| ''[[Sleepy Hollow (TV series)|Sleepy Hollow]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/11/arts/television/2014-emmy-nominations-game-of-thrones-true-detective-among-the-honored.html?_r=0|title=2014 Emmy Nominations: 'Breaking Bad,' 'True Detective' Among the Honored|date=July 10, 2014|work= New York Times|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.briantyler.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|3911}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tyler, Brian}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:American electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:American film score composers]]\n[[Category:American music arrangers]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:American television composers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male television composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Video game composers]]\n[[Category:Classical musicians from California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|BT (musician)}}\n{{about||the auto racer|Brian Tyler (racing driver)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Brian Tyler\n| image              = Brian Tyler Conducts 2011 I.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| caption            = Tyler in 2011\n| birth_name         = Brian Theodore Tyler\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|5|8}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.famouscomposers.net/brian-tyler|title=Brian Tyler - Composer Biography, Facts and Music Compositions|publisher=}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Orange County, California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Composer]]\n* songwriter\n* [[multi-instrumentalist]]\n* [[Conducting|conductor]]\n* [[Arrangement|arranger]]\n* [[disc jockey|DJ]]\n* [[record producer|producer]]\n}}\n| years_active       = 1997\u2013present\n| alma_mater         = {{unbulleted list|[[University of California, Los Angeles]]|[[Harvard University]]}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| alias               = Madsonik\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Film score]]\n* [[Classical music|classical]]\n* [[Rock music|rock]]\n* [[Electronic music|electronic]]\n* [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]\n* [[jazz]]\n}}\n| instrument          = {{flatlist|\n* Drums\n* piano\n* guitar\n* [[double bass|bass]]\n* [[cello]]\n* [[percussion]]\n* [[synthesizer]]\n* [[charango]]\n* [[bouzouki]]\n}}\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n* [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n* [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]]\n* [[Tokyo Philharmonic Orchestra]]\n* [[Philharmonia Orchestra]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL|briantyler.com}}\n| notable_instruments = \n}}\n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''Brian Theodore Tyler''' (born May 8, 1972) is an American [[composer]], [[musician]], [[Conducting|conductor]], [[arranger]], and [[Record producer|producer]], known for his film, television, and video game scores. Tyler scored ''[[Transformers: Prime]]'', ''[[Eagle Eye]]'', ''[[The Expendables (film series)|The Expendables trilogy]]'', ''[[Iron Man 3]]'', ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' with [[Danny Elfman]], ''[[Now You See Me (film)|Now You See Me]]'', and ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|''Crazy Rich Asians'']]'', among others. He also re-arranged the current fanfare of the [[Universal Pictures]] logo that was originally composed by the legendary [[Jerry Goldsmith]], the updated [[Marvel Studios]] logo, which debuted with ''[[Thor: The Dark World]]'' (2013), as well as the ''NFL Theme'' for [[ESPN]], the [[Formula One]] theme and five installments of ''[[Fast & Furious|The Fast and the Furious]]'' franchise.<ref name=\"MarvelFanfare\">{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/21508/introducing_the_new_marvel_studios_logo|title=Introducing the New Marvel Studios Logo|last=Strom|first=Marc|publisher=Marvel|date=November 12, 2013|accessdate=November 12, 2013| archiveurl = http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20131115084009/http%3A//marvel%2Ecom/news/story/21508/introducing_the_new_marvel_studios_logo | archivedate = November 15, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> For his work as a film composer, he has won the [[International Film Music Critics Association|IFMCA Awards]] 2014 Composer of the Year.\n\nHis composition for the film ''[[Last Call (2002 film)|Last Call]]'' earned him the first of three Emmy nominations, a gold record, and was inducted into the music branch of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref name=\"ampas\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2010/06/25/academy-new-members-bono-gabourey-sidibe|title=Academy invites 135 new members|publisher=}}</ref> As of November 2017, his films have grossed $12&nbsp;billion worldwide which puts him in to the top 10 highest-grossing film composers of all time in the category of worldwide box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Composer&id=briantyler.htm|title=Brian Tyler Movie Box Office Results|website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> Tyler has scored 3 of the top 10 films of all time in global box office.\n\n== Life and career ==\nTyler was born and raised in [[Orange County, California]]. His grandfather was [[Academy Award]]-winning art director [[Walter H. Tyler]]. One of his first major influences was his pianist grandmother.<ref>[http://8dio.com/blog/interview-with-brian-tyler/ Interview with Brian Tyler 8Dio] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416182503/http://8dio.com/blog/interview-with-brian-tyler/ |date=April 16, 2014 }}</ref> He holds a [[bachelor's degree]] from the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] and a [[Master's degree|Master's]] from [[Harvard University]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Brian Tyler Bio|url=https://www.briantyler.com/bio|work=briantyler.com}}</ref> Growing up, he taught himself to play at least 30 different types of musical instruments, including drums, piano, guitar, bass, cello, world percussion, synthesizer, charango and bouzouki.<ref>[http://www.corduroymag.com/music/interview-brian-tyler/ Interview: Brian Tyler \u2013 Corduroy magazine] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416230743/http://www.corduroymag.com/music/interview-brian-tyler/ |date=April 16, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nTyler began scoring features shortly after graduating from Harvard. [[Robert Kraft (composer)|Robert Kraft]], who was impressed by Tyler's music, encouraged him to pursue a career in film scoring. He began his career by composing the film score for the [[independent film]] ''Bartender'' (1997), directed by Gabe Torres. The following year, he and [[Red Elvises]] composed the film score for ''[[Six-String Samurai]]'' (1998).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sixstringsamurai.com/tyler.html|title=Sayonara, baby! \u2013 Brian Tyler and ''Six-String Samurai''|accessdate=December 16, 2005|work=Islandlife|last=Comerford|first=Jason| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20051108021842/http://www.sixstringsamurai.com/tyler.html| archivedate = November 8, 2005}}</ref>\n\nTyler's breakthrough came in the early 2000s, after composing for ''[[Frailty (2001 film)|Frailty]]'' (2001). His work on ''[[Last Call (2002 film)|Last Call]]'' (2002) earned him an induction into the music branch of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]].<ref name = ampas /> [[William Friedkin]], after being impressed by his work on ''Frailty'', called Tyler in to begin composing for ''[[The Hunted (2003 film)|The Hunted]]'' (2003), which went on to earn Tyler a [[World Soundtrack Awards 2002|World Soundtrack Award in 2002]] for Best New Film Composer of the Year. Starting in 2003, he began working on big-budget films, including ''[[Timeline (2003 film)|Timeline]]'' (2003), ''[[Godsend (2004 film)|Godsend]]'' (2004), ''[[The Greatest Game Ever Played]]'' (2005), and ''[[Constantine (film)|Constantine]]'' (2005).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/features/article/?id=141|title=SoundtrackNet : Interview \u2013 Brian Tyler|accessdate=December 16, 2005|work=Soundtrack.net| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120204094405/http://www.soundtrack.net/features/article/?id=141 | archivedate = February 4, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref> His score for ''[[The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift]]'' (2006) hit No. 1 on the iTunes soundtrack sales charts, while his soundtrack for ''Children of Dune'' reached No. 4 on the Amazon.com album charts.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}. His cues for ''Children of Dune'' were used in multiple other theatrical film trailers, including ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World|Master and Commander]]'' (2003), ''[[Sahara (2005 film)|Sahara]]'' (2005), ''[[Cinderella Man]]'' (2005), ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' (2005), ''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'' (2008), and ''[[Star Trek (film)|Star Trek]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adtunes.com/forums/showthread.php?t=95121|title=Adtunes Top Ad Music of 2008|accessdate=July 25, 2009|publisher=Adtunes.com| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131008120600/http://adtunes.com/forums/showthread.php?t=95121 | archivedate = October 8, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref> The track \"Summon the Worms\"  was used as a leader for the Dutch show ''Peking Express'', and in the first leaked promotional reel for ''[[The Golden Compass (film)|The Golden Compass]]'' (2007).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=58X4o_41Frc|title=His Dark Materials: The Golden Compass - Sizzle Reel|accessdate=August 23, 2009|publisher=YouTube| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121125140009/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=58X4o_41Frc | archivedate = November 25, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he was hired to compose for ''[[Partition (2007 film)|Partition]]'' (2007), where he had to integrate Indian and Middle Eastern music with orchestral writing. He conducted the orchestral portion of the score with the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoringsessions.com/news/51/|title=Brian Tyler scores Partition|date=June 16, 2006|accessdate=August 23, 2009|work=Scoringsessions.com|last=Goldwasser|first=Dan| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120217194736/http://www.scoringsessions.com/news/51/ | archivedate = February 17, 2012| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2011, Tyler announced that he was currently in talks for scoring the 2011 remake of ''[[Highlander (film)#Remake|Highlander]]'', as well as pilot episodes for the animated series ''[[Transformers: Prime]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.me.com/cbarrywdw03/TheBrianTylerProject/News.html|title=Brian Tyler \u2013 Music Is Life|date=September 5, 2010|accessdate=September 5, 2010|work=web.me.com}}</ref> He went on to score four episodes of the series.\n\nIn 2012, Tyler also scored a new version of the fanfare of the [[Universal Pictures]] logo, originally composed by [[Jerry Goldsmith]], coinciding with the celebration of the studio's 100th anniversary. The new score added elements such as a choir, a bigger emphasis on the movement of the music underneath and a drum cadence at the end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Cb-_9zolcA/|title=Scoring the New Universal Logo - 100th Anniversary (2012) HD|access-date=February 11, 2018|publisher=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to working as a composer, Tyler also wrote and produced the song \"[[Shell Shocked (song)|Shell Shocked]]\" with [[Kill the Noise]], [[Wiz Khalifa]], [[Ty Dolla Sign]], [[Juicy J]] and Moxie that was released in the summer of 2014 under his artist name ''Madsonik''. The track went on to peak at No. 2 on the iTunes hip-hop singles charts and has sold over 500,000 copies.\n\nOn October 12, 2016, he was hired to write and compose the musical score for the 2017 action-adventure film ''[[XXX: Return of Xander Cage]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/10/12/brian-tyler-scoring-xxx-return-of-xander-cage/|title=Brian Tyler Scoring 'xXx: Return of Xander Cage' {{!}} Film Music Reporter|access-date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> He has also contributed to the soundtrack by his stage name Madsonik in a collaboration with Tom Morello and Kill The Noise entitled \"Divebomb\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2017/01/19/edm-exclusive-tom-morello-joins-forces-madsonik-kill-noise-divebomb/|title=Your EDM Exclusive: Madsonik Enlists Tom Morello & Kill The Noise For \"Divebomb\" - Your EDM|date=January 19, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2018, he announced on Twitter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BrianTylerMusic/status/969689232024461312|title=Twitter}}</ref> that he had been hired by [[Formula One]] to write a brand new theme that was released on March 23.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2018/3/must-see--watch-f1s-new-opening-title-sequence-.html|title=MUST SEE \u2013 Watch F1's new opening title sequence|work=Formula1.com|access-date=2018-03-24}}</ref> In August 2018, a 27-track soundtrack composed by Tyler for the cable TV series ''[[Yellowstone (American TV series)|Yellowstone]]'' was issued on August 17, 2018 in CD format and for mp3 download on Amazon.<ref>Amazon CD download services. Yellowstone soundtrack. Retrieved August 29, 2018. [https://www.amazon.com/Yellowstone-Original-Television-Soundtrack-Brian/dp/B07G7J7Q5N/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1534788248&sr=8-1&keywords=yellowstone+soundtrack+cd]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Bartender''\n| Gabe Torres\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| 1998\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Six-String Samurai]]''\n| [[Lance Mungia]]\n| Composed with [[Red Elvises]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1999\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[The Settlement (1999 film)|The Settlement]]''\n| Mark Steilen\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[The 4th Floor (1999 film)|The 4th Floor]]''\n| Josh Klausner\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Simon Sez]]''\n|[[Kevin Alyn Elders]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2000\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Panic (2000 film)|Panic]]''\n| [[Henry Bromell]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Shadow Hours]]''\n| Isaac H. Eaton\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Four Dogs Playing Poker]]''\n| [[Paul Rachman]]\n| {{N/a}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Terror Tract]]''\n| Lance W. Dreesen<br />Clint Hutchison\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2001\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''Plan B''\n| [[Greg Yaitanes]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |''[[Frailty (2001 film)|Frailty]]''\n|[[Bill Paxton]]\n|First collaboration with Bill Paxton<br> Nominated- [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards|Fangoria Chainsaw Award for Best Score]]<br>Nominated- [[International Film Music Critics Association|IFMCA Award for Best Original Score for a Horror/Thriller Film]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2002\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |''[[Bubba Ho-tep]]''\n|[[Don Coscarelli]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Vampires: Los Muertos]]''\n| [[Tommy Lee Wallace]]\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2003\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |''[[Darkness Falls (2003 film)|Darkness Falls]]''\n|[[Jonathan Liebesman]]\n| First collaboration with Jonathan Liebesman\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[The Hunted (2003 film)|The Hunted]]''\n| [[William Friedkin]]\n| First collaboration with William Friedkin\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[The Big Empty (2003 film)|The Big Empty]]''\n| Steve Anderson\n| {{N/A}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[Timeline (2003 film)|Timeline]]''\n|[[Richard Donner]]\n| Replaced [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2004\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |''[[The Final Cut (2004 film)|The Final Cut]]''\n|[[Omar Naim]]\n|Nominated- [[International Film Music Critics Association|IFMCA Award for Best Original Score for a Horror/Thriller Film]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"te